node.text:
If all of your debts are paid in full and the accounts are closed, you'll have what's called an "indeterminable" credit score after about 6 months. Then, you'll be able to do what's called "manual underwriting" to buy a home. All that means is that the mortgage company will do what banks used to do all the time when someone bought a home. They'll actually review your finances to check out whether or not you're in a position to pay back the loan.

A mortgage is the only type of debt, I'm okay with. Just make sure that the payment is no more than 25% of your take-home pay on no more than a 15-year mortgage at a fixed rate. I want your house to be a financial blessing in your life, not a financial curse.

You CAN have financial peace. You just need to take your time and do the math to make sure things are done right.

Thanks to Dr. @johndelony for joining me on this call.

node.text:
There's an addictive thrill that can come with the risk on these sorts of things. Although a lot of people are having a lot of fun with this right now, it's important to not confuse a get-rich-quick scenario with an actual, proven wealth-building plan. Just because a few people won the lottery one time does NOT make it an investment strategy that you should use. If you're debt-free with a full emergency fund, and you want to use some fun/entertainment money that you've budgeted for to play around with these things, I'm not gonna get mad at you, but I don't recommend it… and I certainly don't do this myself. If you REALLY want to play around with single stocks, just make sure that no more than 10% of your net worth is tied up in them. This is to ensure that things don't go overboard to the point that it can actually impact your net worth in a negative way if and when things go south. 

Reminder: I only recommend investing in mutual funds and real estate that's paid for in full.

node.text:
The 7 Baby Steps help you bring focus to your money goals.

As you're working on those first three Baby Steps, you need to take them one at a time, in order. FOCUS is the key during this season of your money journey. Don't try to save up a bigger emergency fund and pay a little bit here and there on your debt. Focus on saving up just that first $1,000, and THEN dive straight into focusing completely on paying off debt. Every extra penny counts. Then, once you're debt-free, put that debt paying focus toward saving your full emergency fund of 3-6 months of expenses.

These three steps are a fast track to get you to Baby Step 4 where you'll be able to begin investing 15% of your income for retirement. That's when you get to start seeing your money work for YOU, instead of the other way around.

Stay focused and stay the course. You got this! 

#debtfreecommunity

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Dave Ramsey on July 22, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Notes HOW TO MAKE A BUDGET 1. List your income for the month. 2. List your expenses for the month. 3. Subtract your expenses from your income. 4. This should work out to equal zero.'.

node.text:
It's important to make a plan for EVERY dollar in your budget.

Expenses include: giving, saving, and spending.

Each person or family's budget will look different depending on what Baby Step they're on and their specific situation. 

@rachelcruze says, "A budget doesn't limit your freedom, it GIVES you freedom." Even if you're struggling financially, making a plan for your money will give you peace of mind. A plan always does.

If you've lost your income recently, focus on covering the 4 Walls (food, utilities, shelter, and transportation - in that order), and pile up cash while you weather this financial storm. 

Give each dollar in your plan a job until every dollar is accounted for. 

#debtfreecommunity

node.text:
Debt is DUMB. Cash is KING.

A debit card will do everything that a credit card can do, EXCEPT put you into debt.

There will probably be some time between steps 1 and 2 on this list, but cutting up the card to stop the temptation to spend is SO important. Pay it off as quickly as you can, then make the call to cancel. The credit card company will probably try to give you a hard time or offer you incentives to keep the account open. Don't give in. You've said "NO" to debt. Make sure to get a confirmation of the cancellation in writing, and never look back! 

#debtfreecommunity

node.text:
🎉 YOU DID IT!! You set a goal and you achieved it. Way to go!

#repost @istyle_

1, 2, 3, call me debt free Ki 😭🙌🏾

Where do I even begin?! I remember when I graduated from college and received a letter that I would have to start paying back my student loans in 6 months. 🥴

At the time I didn’t have a job lined up and according to some people it would take me the rest of my life to pay them off 🙃.

When it was time to start repaying them, I choose to get on a 10 yr plan so that I could pay them off sooner. Even after paying them for a couple of years it felt like I wasn’t making much progress because of the interest that was accruing.

Fast forward to the beginning of 2018 I decided that enough was enough. I wanted to retire my student loans for good. The only problem was I didn’t really hear anyone talking about paying off debt or see anyone that looked like me doing it.

After doing some research online I came across @daveramsey and it felt like an answered prayer. I discovered a community of people from all different backgrounds and even many that looked like me that were paying off debt. After hearing many inspiring stories, I knew that debt freedom was possible for me to so I got to work.

The biggest thing that helped me during my journey was getting on a strict budget. Thankfully I didn’t have any other debt so I was able to free up income by decreasing my expenses. In addition I picked up a side hustle baby sitting to help increase my income to pay off my debt faster.

One of the greatest blessings came during 2020 when there was a freeze on student loan payments. This meant that all my payments would go directly toward the principle and would help me to reach my goal sooner. 🙌🏾

So here I am 3.5 years later with $74,106.46 gone and officially debt free. I’m thankful for God’s provision throughout this entire journey. And I’m thankful for my husband for cheering and supporting me every step of the way. This has been such a huge milestone in our first year of marriage and I couldn’t have done it without him!

I pray that sharing our story will inspire you that debt freedom is possible for you too. ❤️

#debtfreecommunity #debtfreescream

node.text:
Here's a breakdown of why I recommend people get 10-12 times their annual income in TERM life insurance...

If the worst happens, Alex's family can take care of some immediate expenses, and then invest the remainder of the money from his life insurance policy into a mutual fund. (Always get in touch with a trusted investing professional to help with this.) They would then see an annual return on the investment that would be similar to his current income. This money would help them long term if the worst case scenario were to happen.

If someone depends on you or your income, you NEED life insurance.

For stay-at-home parents, I recommend a term policy valued between $250,000 - $400,000.

I only recommend term life insurance. Why? You get the same amount of coverage for a fraction of the price of a whole life policy. A term policy lasts for a set number of years (usually 20) and you pay a low rate each month for the coverage you need. At the end of the term, yes, that policy has ended, but what the critics fail to remember is that you've had 20 years of affordable coverage. In that time, you can use the money you’re saving to pay off debt, save for emergencies, and invest the difference you would have thrown away on a more expensive whole life policy. If you're working to get out of debt and following the 7 Baby Steps, you'll be covered with your investments after 20 years, and you won't need life insurance anymore. Don't throw your money away. Think for yourself and get the coverage you need, not the policy that someone making a commission wants to sell you on.

node.text:
The 7 Baby Steps work, when you WORK them. I hear people say they're working the Dave Ramsey plan...ish. Or they're doing Dave Ramsey...ish.

If you "ish" this stuff, you're going to get "ish" results.

If you want to finally get things moving and make REAL progress with money, it's going to take intentionality and sacrifice. 

No more "ish". Go allllllllll in. Hold nothing back. 

Cut up the credit cards. Make a budget. Sell something. Take an extra job. Say no to things you used to use debt for. Run from debt like the plague. Get MAD about the things you haven't been able to do because of a car payment, a student loan payment, and all the other payments society tells you are normal. Turn your back on your old way of thinking about money and make decisions that will benefit the future you. You are NOT a victim. Your life belongs to you and you can take control of it. 

It's worth it and you CAN do it. 

No more playing around. Your future depends on the decisions you make today. It's time to make the right ones. 

#debtfreecommunity
